<HEADLINE> Turkish Forces in Northern Iraq to Pursue PKK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Some 5,000 to 7,000 Turkish troops,
backed by helicopter gunships, crossed into northern Iraq early on
Sunday in an operation against rebels of the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK), military sources said.
</P>
<P>
The troops pushed 10 kilometers into northern Iraq and clashed
with PKK rebels in several places.
</P>
<P>
The operation is apparently aimed at warning PKK not to regroup
its militants in the Turkish territory.
</P>
<P>
"It has been observed that many PKK groups have been moving
toward the Turkish border. Hence security forces launched the
operation this morning," said the military sources.
</P>
<P>
The operation ran in parallel with an action by some 10,000
Turkish troops sweeping the mountains near the Turkish towns of
Tunceli and Bingol in mid-eastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the forces in northern Iraq, up to 50,000 troops are
being deployed on the Turkish-Iraqi border, ready to take part in a
larger operation.
</P>
<P>
In response to a call issued by the imprisoned PKK leader
Abdullah Ocalan after being sentenced to death, PKK rebel forces
announced a ceasefire and reportedly retreated into bases in
northern Iraq in February.
</P>
<P>
But the Turkish military described the call as a ploy to win
time in order to stage a come-back.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1991 Gulf War, northern Iraq has been under practical
control by two rival Iraqi Kurdish factions independent of the
central Iraqi government. One of the factions has been fighting the
PKK alongside the Turkish army.
</P>
<P>
But each time the Turkish troops intruded into northern Iraq,
they were condemned by Baghdad as an encroachment upon the Iraqi
territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
