<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Racist Attacks in N.Ireland Draw Concern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The police said the attack on two Chinese men in south Belfast
on Sunday morning was racially motivated, the BBC reported.
</P>
<P>
Both men were chased and beaten by a gang near Delhi Street, in
the Ormeau Road area of the city. One of the men was taken to
hospital with a broken finger and a head wound.
</P>
<P>
Anna Manwah Watson of the Chinese Welfare Association said the
attack was not an isolated incident.
</P>
<P>
"In the last three months we have received reports from about
10 families from the Chinese community complaining about
harassment at their homes and restaurant, with people throwing
stones and causing trouble. To hear about this attack would
certainly scare the Chinese community even more," she said.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to remind the community that the Chinese
community has been here for over 30 years. We have stood by the
wider community right through the Troubles. We have worked and
provided a very good service for the community whether it is in
Protestant or Catholic areas," the BBC quoted Anna as saying.
</P>
<P>
Alliance Party leader Sean Neeson condemned the attack as "
cowardly and very worrying".
</P>
<P>
"I am deeply concerned at the growing number of racially
motivated crimes in Northern Ireland and would ask for serious
consideration to be given to the introduction of Hates Crimes
Legislation here," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
