<HEADLINE> Kuwait Hopes OPEC Deal Helps Stabilize Oil Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait on Sunday voiced hope
that the newly-reached agreement on increasing oil production of
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) will help
stabilize oil prices.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after its weekly session, the Kuwaiti
cabinet expressed hope that "the results of the agreement will help
achieve stability" in the interests of both oil producing and
consuming countries.
</P>
<P>
Oil ministers of OPEC's 11 members, including Kuwait, began a
meeting in Vienna on March 27 to decide on the output policy after
OPEC's one-year production cuts agreement expired on March 31.
</P>
<P>
OPEC's output squeeze policy had at first lifted the oil prices
from abyss, or a 10-year low of about eight U.S. dollars a barrel
at the beginning of 1999, and then pushed the prices to a nine-year
high of over 30 dollars last month.
</P>
<P>
On March 29, nine of the 11 ministers signed, following tough
discussion, an agreement to increase their output by 1.45 million
barrels per day starting Saturday, with an "aim to keep the oil
prices at reasonable levels."
</P>
<P>
Iran, which didn't sign the new deal along with Iraq, has also
reportedly agreed to increase its production.
</P>
<P>
OPEC also groups Algeria, Indonesia, Libya, Qatar, Nigeria,
Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates and Venezuela. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
