<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Final Status Talks Make No Progress in Washington: PNA Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian chief negotiator to the
final-status talks Yasser Abd-Rabbo said the talks held in
Washington between March 21 and 28 failed to make substantial
progress.
</P>
<P>
The talks focused on three main issues, namely the land, the
refugees and the future relations between Palestine and Israel, he
told reporters here on Sunday
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israelis discussed the last stage of the
redeployment of Israeli troops but failed to make headway due to
Israel's refusal to define the borders of Jewish settlements,
Jerusalem and the Israeli military bases which represent a
prerequisite of charting the maps of the last redeployment, Abd-
Rabbo said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Oslo accord, Israel should withdraw its troops from
the Palestinian territories occupied during the 1967 Middle East
war except for the Jewish settlements, Jerusalem and the military
bases that could be dealt with in the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
So far Israel turned over the Gaza Strip wholly and 43 percent
of the West Bank to the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) while
retaining security control over the Jewish settlements there.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday evening PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat said the
Washington talks were still in a preliminary stage, adding that the
talks did not discuss serious issues.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to hold further talks in Washington on
April 6.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the Palestinians said on Sunday that
Arafat will meet U.S. President Bill Clinton late April in
Washington in a bid to push forward the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Under the Sharm El-Sheikh memorandum, the Palestinians and
Israelis are scheduled to reach a framework agreement by next May
as a prelude to signing a permanent peace treaty on September 13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
