<HEADLINE> Zambian Ruling Party Expels Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lusaka, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's ruling Movement for
Multi-Party Democracy (MMD)announced here Sunday that its
Information and Publicity Secretary George Mwambazi and Lusaka
province Chairperson for Women's Affairs Rose Zimba have been
expelled from the party for alleged disobeying party regulations.
</P>
<P>
Several other MMD members have also been expelled for similar
reasons, Lusaka Province Minister Sonny Mulenga announced at a
press briefing.
</P>
<P>
He said Mwambazi and Zimba have been expelled from the party
following dark corner meetings they had been holding in support of
Environment and Natural Resources Minister Ben Mwila together with
some other party members who had also been campaigning for Mwila.
</P>
<P>
"At a Provincial Executive Committee (PEC) meeting held here
yesterday (Saturday), we decided that Mwambazi and Zimba be
expelled from the party because they had been holding dark corner
meetings," he said.
</P>
<P>
He categorically stated that MMD cadres in Lusaka province
would follow directions of the MMD National Executive Committee
(NEC) and would respect the decision of President Frederick
Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Mulenga meanwhile advised Mwila to form his own political party
if he wanted to be president.
</P>
<P>
Mwila, one of the country's richest with a business empire
spanning manufacturing, construction, finance and fertilizers,
helped Chiluba defeat former President Kenneth Kaunda in the
elections in 1991 and now is seen as a leading candidate to
replace his nephew in the next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
But Chiluba said in September last year that he would ensure
that his uncle Mwila does not become the country's president.
</P>
<P>
Recently Mwila has been accused of defying the party decision
not to start campaign at present stage.  
</P>
</TEXT>
