<HEADLINE> U.S. Defense Secretary Visits Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen arrived in Israel Sunday evening for a brief visit at the
start of his 12-day tour of the ten countries in the region, aimed
at boosting multilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
A senior Israel defense official has said that one of Cohen's
objectives in the visit is to examine how to build a broader
security network to enable Middle East allies to collaborate to
counter joint threats like terrorism and possible biological and
chemical warfare.
</P>
<P>
Cohen is scheduled to hold talks Monday morning with Prime
Minister and Defense Minister Ehud Barak, before leaving Israel for
Jordan and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
In the talks, the two are expected to discuss military
cooperation between the two countries, the 17-billion-U.S.- dollar
U.S. defense assistance Israel wants to accompany any peace deal
with Syria, and other security issues concerning the peace process.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, in a speech to American-Turkish Council in
Washington, Cohen described the Middle East as a neighborhood where
terror is tangible and palpable and said much of the future
security of the region will depend on actions by Iraq and Iran.
</P>
<P>
This is Cohen's sixth tour of the region, which will also take
him to Nigeria, Qatar, Bahrain, kuwait, Saudi Arabia, the United
Arab Emirates and Oman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
