<HEADLINE> S. African Gov't Urged to Attract More Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The South African Communist
Party (SACP) on Sunday stressed that the government should use the
budget to draw more foreign direct investment for infrastructure
development and job creation.
</P>
<P>
"Much needs to be done in order to attract the flows of foreign
direct investment," SACP's secretary-general Blade Nzimande told
South African Press Association after the party's central
committee meeting here.
</P>
<P>
He said the committee noticed that since mid 1996, the party
has been trying to attract substantial foreign investment through
a program of "self- imposed fiscal austerity".
</P>
<P>
"Whatever contribution the austerity program may have made to
stabilization, the foreign direct investment flows have been
disappointing, and financial liberalization has seen a net outflow
of capital," Nzimande said.
</P>
<P>
The SACP is planning to play a more active role in the
budgetary process.
</P>
<P>
Nzimande explained :"We will, within alliance (with African
National Congress), seek to shape budgetary priorities that are
more aligned with our vision of infrastructural development and
industrial policy programs as the key accelerator for growth, job
creation and development.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth requires an economically active government
which is capable and willing to plan, coordinate and discipline
the capital resources of the society, he emphasized. 
</P>
