<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kaunda Reaffirms Retirement from Politics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambian former President and leader
of the biggest opposition party, the United National Independence
Party (UNIP), Kenneth Kaunda reaffirmed here Sunday his decision
to quit party politics.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, 76, told a press conference held in the
Intercontinental Hotel that he will not contest any position at
the UNIP National Congress to be held at the end of this month and
early May.
</P>
<P>
"I have made a firm decision and committment to retire from
active politics and devote more of my time to other pressing
concerns," he told hundreds of reporters and his supporters
crowding the hall.
</P>
<P>
He said the retirement decision is neither as abrupt nor as
sudden as it appears, adding that he had been carrying out wide
consultations both within and outside his party.
</P>
<P>
He had also carried out extensive consultations within and
outside the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda expressed his hope and confidence that UNIP will find a
suitable leadership among the many young people.
</P>
<P>
+I will be handing over power to the new leadership and
particularly to the new president of the United National
Independence Party willingly and confidently knowing that I will
always be there to support him or her to the fullest. Together we
will take this mighty party to higher heights,+ Kaunda said.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that under no circumstance will he abandon the
party that he has led for more than 40 years.
</P>
<P>
"I will always be available for consultations and whenever I
maybe requested I will always do everything possible to help," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda said even in retirement he will remain an ordinary but a
strong and active member of the UNIP.
</P>
<P>
He said "I will not interfere but I will help if need be."
</P>
<P>
He said that he will also never relinquish his responsibilities
to his country, adding that "I shall therefore not hesitate to
play my part in seeking for solutions to the problems that may
affect our people."
</P>
<P>
If necessary, he will take action against any injustice that
any government will perpetuate. That includes a UNIP government,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Almost a decade later the situation in the country is very much
worse than at the time he handed over power, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The levels of poverty are depressing and painful and the
massive numbers of once employed people who now have little
dignity has brought shame to us all," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the country's general elections to be held next year Kaunda
said he had been carrying out a series of consultations with other
opposition parties over the last few weeks. It was brought to his
attention that it might be easier for a united opposition, working
together to successfully emerge victorious at the elections.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda expressed his confidence that his party has gone through
over the last few years, it has regained its confidence.
</P>
<P>
Given a fair and level playing field, UNIP is capable of
electoral victory and it is possible for the party to form a
government once again, Kaunda said.
</P>
<P>
Last week Kaunda announced in South Africa that he will retire
from active politics.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda ruled Zambia after its independence from British
colonial rule in 1964 until 1991, when he was defeated by
incumbent President Frederick Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 elections Kaunda was barred from contesting the
position because his Malawian parentage.
</P>
<P>
In that year a constitutional amendment was adopted to bar
those whose parents are foreign immigrants from contesting the
country's presidency.
</P>
<P>
However, Kaunda had vowed repeatedly to run for the presidency
in the next general elections despite the government utterance
that Kaunda is not qualified for it.
</P>
<P>
His rival Chiluba has repeatedly urged him to quit party
politics to be respected as founding father of the country like
Nyerere of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda resigned from UNIP soon after his party lost in the 1991
 elections but he returned to UNIP in 1994 and was elected UNIP
president in 1995.
</P>
<P>
On December 25 of 1997 three days after his return from
overseas trip Kaunda was arrested for his alleged involvement in
the coup attempt of October 28 of 1997.
</P>
<P>
On June 1, 1998, Kaunda was released and in return for the
release three days later Kaunda announced his retirement from
party politics.
</P>
<P>
However at the end of 1998 Kaunda vowed not to retire, saying
no body can prevent him from contesting the 2001 elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
