<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Africa Vows to Bring Perpetrators of Nightclub Tragedy to Justice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 2 (Xinhua) --The South African government
would see to it that the perpetrators of a nightclub tragedy in
which 13 children died be brought to justice, Deputy President
Jacob Zuma said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Zuma addressed a memorial service in Chatsworth near Durban in
memory of the children who died in what has now become known as
"black Friday".
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people, mostly from the Chatsworth community,
attended the memorial service in support of the grieving
families.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, two young men allegedly acting on orders from
Sivanthan Chetty, 39, owner of the Silver Slipper nightclub in
Chatsworth, detonated the teargas canister inside the full and
apparently badly ventilated club where about 800 children were
celebrating the end of the school term.
</P>
<P>
In the panic and hysteria that followed the children stormed
down a narrow stairway and under the pressure a wall collapsed on
them.
</P>
<P>
Eleven children were trampled to death, one died on the way to
hospital, another later died in hospital from lung damage and some
150 were injured, a number of them critical.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said he would personally like to see justice taking its
course in this case.
</P>
<P>
"The judgement in this case must be an example for all," said
Zuma.
</P>
<P>
"From national government's side we would like to see that the
law is followed to the end to deal with the perpetrators of this
crime." he was quoted as saying by South African Press
Association.
</P>
<P>
He told the crowd the tragedy was a challenge to the whole
of South Africa and not only to Chatsworth to find out what was
wrong with society.
</P>
<P>
"Something has gone fundamentally wrong with our society, he
said, adding that "people worship money at all cost and they use
money for activities  that is not good for society."
</P>
<P>
Zuma said it was clear that the problem was with the adults
and not with the children who attended the club.
</P>
<P>
"We need to create appropriate forms of entertainment for
our children," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Be strong, be comforted...this tragedy is calling on all
of us to do something about our society... This tragedy must be
the last of its kind, " Zuma said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
