<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Hospitalized for "Over-exhaustion" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi
was taken to a Tokyo hospital Sunday morning for "over-exhaustion",
Chief Cabinet Secretary Mikio Aoki said Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi was taken to a hospital in Tokyo around 1 a.m., and is
undergoing tests, the top Japanese government spokesman told a
press conference late Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the premier's condition was unknown, Aoki said,
adding that it will be disclosed as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Aoki said Obuchi was conscious when he met him in the evening.
</P>
<P>
Aoki would be named acting prime minister, if necessary. That
had not been done as of late Sunday, Aoki said, but the
possibility was under consideration.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi had been busy dealing with the recent eruption of Mt.
Usu in Japan's northernmost prefecture of Hokkaido.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, the Japanese prime minister held talks with
leaders of his coalition partners, the New Komeito party and the
Liberal Party, over the breakup of the tripartite coalition.
</P>
</TEXT>
