<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, April 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel will not allow any foreign troop deployment
over its northern border that threatens its unilateral withdrawal
from south Lebanon, Israeli military sources said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Any foreign troop deployment over Israel's northern border
would be regarded by Israel as an infringement of the "red lines"
between Israeli and Syrian troops in Lebanon, the sources told
Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
The military sources made these remarks while commenting on the
Lebanese Defense Minister Ghazi Zaiter's statement on Saturday
that Beirut may ask Syrian troops to deploy in south Lebanon after
Israel's pullout there. (Israel-Lebanon)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea Sunday began to take measures to prevent
the spread of vesicular disease among livestock in Hongsong County,
South Chungchong Province as scores of heads of cattle and pigs
there were found infected with the disease.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry has banned exit of
people, vehicles and livestock from the infected areas in Hongsong
and slaughtered 58 heads of cattle and 35 pigs within 500 meter
radius from a farm where the cases were spotted.
</P>
<P>
The disease, which causes blisters on the mouth and hoof of
livestock, was first discovered last Monday and killed dozens of
livestock in Paju, Kyonggi Province in the country. (SKorea-
Vesicular Disease)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Foreign ministers from African and European countries
met Sunday ahead of the Africa-Europe summit to finalize the
agenda that will be discussed at the summit.
</P>
<P>
The summit, sponsored by the Organization of African Unity and
the European Union, is to discuss economic, political and social
development issues and bilateral cooperation in these fields.
</P>
<P>
But before the meeting, African and EU countries differed over
which issues should take priority in the upcoming discussion. (
Egypt-Africa-Europe-FM Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi was taken to a
Tokyo hospital for unspecified ailment late Sunday, Japan's NHK
television reported.
</P>
<P>
The report gave no details on his present health condition,
but said a government spokesman would give a briefing at 11:30 p.m.
(1430 GMT). (Japan-PM-Hospitalized)  
