<HEADLINE> Syrian FM Denies to Deploy Army in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Syrian Foreign Minister
Faruk Shareh Sunday denied the saying that Syria would pour into
south Lebanon after Israel's withdrawal, People's Voice radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
Shareh has delivered a message from Syrian President Hafez Assad
to Lebanese President Emile Lahoud concerning "the latest
development in the region and result of Geneva summit" after his
arrival earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
On Lebanese Defense Minister Ghazi Zuetir's speech of inviting
Syrian troops into south Lebanon in the event of Israel's
unilateral pullout from south Lebanon, Shareh said this was
Zuetir's personal point of view, adding that the two countries
should speak in one voice or Israel will benefit from their
divergence.
</P>
<P>
Zuetir said Friday that his country would ask Syria to garrison
south Lebanon following Israel's withdrawal. Lebanese official
source later declared it was Zuetir's personal position.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a self-styled 15-kilometer-deep security zone
in 1985 in south Lebanon with a claimed aim of protecting its north
from cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
Last month Israeli cabinet passed Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
plan to pullout its troops from south Lebanon with or without
framework agreement with Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, stations some 350,000
troops in the country. The two countries have repeatedly reiterated
the simultaneity of two peace tracks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Damascus has been demanding that Israel commit to a full
withdrawal from the strategic Golan Plateau back to the borders
before June 4, 1967, while Israel has rejected the Syrian demands.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish state is keen to maintain full control of access to
the Sea of Galilee, the main source of fresh water for Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Syrian peace talks had been frozen for four years before
they re-opened in the United States in December.
</P>
<P>
But the talks quickly collapsed over the Golan Heights, but both
sides have said the door remains open for further negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss is scheduled to visit
Damascus on Monday for further talks with Syrian leaders on the
peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
