<DOCNO> XIE20000402.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Seeking Strategic Partnership With EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of
the Organization of African Unity (OAU) said here
Sunday that African countries are looking for a
new and strategic partnership with Europe.
</P>
<P>
"The partnership should be able to help us
carry out economic reforms, including structural
adjustment, in the light of economic
globalization," Sigh Makhan, OAU assistant
secretary-general for Eastern Africa, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The OAU official made the remarks just before
the Africa-Europe foreign ministerial meeting,
which is to make final preparations for the first
Africa-Europe summit due on Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The summit, under the auspices of the OAU and
the European Union (EU), is expected to be
attended by heads of state and government, or
their representatives, of most of the 15 EU member
states and 53 African countries.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the ministerial meeting and the
forthcoming summit, Makhan said the African
countries want to discuss issues "of primary
concern to us," particularly economic issues and
debt issues.
</P>
<P>
African countries, with a total external debts
of over 350 billion U.S. dollars, are seeking debt
reduction or forgiveness, more financial aid and
investment from EU.
</P>
<P>
The African countries also want to discuss with
the rich EU countries removing trade barriers "so
that our products can have a broad market access
not only in Europe but elsewhere," he added.
</P>
<P>
Makhan hoped both African and EU countries,
many of which former colonial powers in Africa,
would make "integrated efforts" towards the unity,
security and stability of the war-and-poverty-
plagued African continent.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want a divided Africa. And this is
what we are telling our partners and they should
not do anything that will undermine our efforts to
integrate the continent," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
