<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Ministry Considers Granting Mossad Legal Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Justice Ministry is
considering giving Israel's secret intelligence service Mossad a
formal legal status, the ministry' spokesman disclosed on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Justice Minister Yossi Beilin is mulling the idea and doesn't
exclude the possibility of legalizing the role of Mossad, Israel
Radio quoted spokesman Amir Abramovitz as saying.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Ha'aretz daily reported the possible role-changing
will include defining its aims, clarifying its criminal
responsibility and formalizing its methods of investigation.
</P>
<P>
Mossad, which is responsible for gathering intelligence outside
Israel and conducting "special operations" abroad, doesn't have a
specific and clear legal role right now, according to Abramovitz.
</P>
<P>
Mossad, led by a chief appointed by Israeli prime minister
directly, has unconventional operational methods and traditionally
acts independently.
</P>
<P>
The chief's name was permitted to appear in media only several
years ago.
</P>
<P>
Although Mossad is regarded as one of the most successful and
efficient intelligence agencies, its reputation had been tarnished
in recent years by a series of botched attacks.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, its agents used purloined Canadian passports in a
assassination attempt on an Islamic militant leader in Jordan,
whose failure led to a diplomatic dispute between Israel and Canada
and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
One year later, Mossad agent's name again emerged disgracefully
in front pages as their wiretapping of a "target" in Switzerland
was tracked down by their smart Swiss craft brother and were caught
on the spot.
</P>
<P>
Last year, an ex-Mossad intelligence official was also convicted
by an Israeli court for fabricating reports on Syria, a
professional scandal tarnishing Mossad's fame further.
</P>
<P>
Some observers has pointed out that Mossad's flawed structure
and undemocratic organizational frameworks are some of the main
reasons for the failures.
</P>
<P>
Thus, they believe the agency's possible role-changing is
another indication of the trend in the security-paramount country,
in which some once notoriously clandestine organizations are urged
to accustom to a more democratic and open society.
</P>
<P>
"If something is clear and everyone knows what are the borders
or the powers, what is right and what is wrong, where is the red
line and borders of the Shin Bet and the Mossad, it can help
clarify the situation," Abramovitz said.
</P>
<P>
The domestic Shin Bet, or the General Security Service, was
prohibited last year by Israel's Supreme Court from using physical
pressure, which once was a routine measure by the service to get
information from Palestinian detainees.
</P>
<P>
Israel's Knesset (Parliament) is considering formalizing the
role of the Shin Bet either, Abramovitz said.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) will
also declassify the Commands of the General Staff in several
months.
</P>
<P>
According to Israel Radio, senior officials said the orders are
to be made public in order to bring more transparency to the army.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
