<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Rejects Lebanese DM's Statement on Troop Deployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Defense Minister Ghazi
Zuetir's statement on Syrian troop deployment in south Lebanon
after Israeli troop withdrawal was "impractical," Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Barak told the weekly cabinet meeting that "Zuetir's statement
concerning Syrian troop deployment in south Lebanon reflects the
sense of distress over the prospects of Israel's withdrawal."
</P>
<P>
Barak also expressed pessimism about the possibility of
restarting the Israeli-Syrian peace talks as U.S. President Bill
Clinton failed to reach an agreement on this issue during his
meeting in Geneva last Sunday with Syrian President Hafez al-Assad.
</P>
<P>
Israel will not allow Syria to deploy troops over its northern
border that threatens its unilateral withdrawal from south Lebanon,
Israeli military sources said earlier.
</P>
<P>
Any Syrian troop deployment over Israel's northern border would
be regarded by Israel as an infringement of the "red lines" between
Israeli and Syrian troops in Lebanon, the sources pointed out.
</P>
<P>
If Israel withdraws unilaterally from the security zone by
July, "this raises the possibility to the Lebanese government to
ask Syria to send its troops to the south with the Lebanese army,"
Zuetir was quoted as saying on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Zuetir said he wanted to make it clear that his statement was
just his personal opinion and not Lebanon's official policy,
adding "the aim of such a request is not to make Syria protect
Israeli northern borders, but to put Tel Aviv in the range of the
Syrian rockets."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Zuetir's statement, Danny Naveh, who heads the
Likud's reaction team, said Sunday that Israel must be tough and
must demand a total withdrawal of Syrian troops from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Syria, the major power broker in neighboring Lebanon, deploys
about 35,000 troops in the country as peace keepers.
</P>
<P>
Syria would at this stage sit on the sideline in Lebanon and
avoid a direct confrontation with Israel, Israeli Tourism Minister
Amnon Lipkin-Shahak said Sunday, adding that "were Syrians to sit
on the Lebanese border, this would create a whole new situation."
</P>
<P>
Justice Minister Yossi Beilin said Saturday night that Zuetir's
statement reflects the tragedy of Lebanese-Syrian relations, and
that any new developments in south Lebanon after Israel's
withdrawal should be carefully monitored by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Chief of General Staff of the Israel Defense Forces Lt.Gen.
Shaul Mofaz briefed the cabinet Sunday on the situation in southern
Lebanon and on preparations under way for the July withdrawal which
has been approved by the cabinet last month.
</P>
<P>
Israel expects the withdrawal to be carried out in the context
of U.N. Security Council Resolution 425, which calls for the
deployment of either Lebanese or international forces on the
border.
</P>
<P>
Barak has said that if Israel is attacked from Lebanon after the
withdrawal, Israel will not hesitate to retaliate.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a security zone in south Lebanon in 1985 with a
self-proclaimed purpose of protecting its northern border from
cross-border guerrilla attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
