<HEADLINE> Portuguese FM Calls for Joint Efforts to Solve African Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Portugal's Foreign Minister Jaime
Gama on Sunday called for joint efforts by the European Union (EU)
and African countries to deal with the social and economic problems
in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Tackling environment, AIDS, poverty and a number of other social
affairs "is a common responsibility, we must address those issues
in cooperation," Gama told reporters after a meeting by the foreign
ministers of the 15 EU members, which preceded a joint Africa-
Europe foreign ministerial meeting Sunday noon.
</P>
<P>
"And that is the reason why we are searching for a Euro-African
strategic partnership, which is being created in this (upcoming)
first Africa-Europe summit," he said.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of African and EU countries will meet here on Monday and
Tuesday to discuss economic, political and social issues in Africa
and bilateral cooperation in these fields. The joint foreign
ministerial meeting was to lay the final touches for the upcoming
summit.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the differences over the subjects between the EU
and Africa, Gama said "we are working very intensively (to bridge
the gap) for several months. This (summit) meeting has also been
prepared for several months. And now we are at foreign ministers'
level. We are preparing the last paragraphs where we were not
agreeing, moving to an effective agreement."
</P>
<P>
While the EU countries see the summit as a political event to
discuss conflict prevention, human rights issues, good governance,
fighting against corruption in Africa, the African countries are
equally determined to put emphasis on the critically key issues of
trade, investment, debts and aid.
</P>
<P>
On the possibility of promising to cut or write off Africa's
heavy burden of debts by EU countries, Gama said "we have announced
that, for the most poor countries, we have a strategy of debt
relief which is sound and will be addressed in the appropriate
framework of the international financial institutions."
</P>
<P>
"Also, we have targets for alleviating Africa's poverty and
contributing to their efforts in close cooperation with the African
states. We are working seriously upon that," he added.
</P>
<P>
The debt problem is not only an African problem, it is also
important for international trade and economy and Europe, too,
because it is crucial and effective for the world economy to
resolve the issue, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The total external debts of African countries, where about 44
percent of the population, especially in sub-Saharan Africa, live
well below the poverty line, amounted to 350 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
