<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Launches Campaign To Confiscate Thai Tuna Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIYADH, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Saudi government has launched a
nationwide campaign to confiscate 15 kinds of Thai tuna products
believed to contain the genetically-engineering processed soybeans,
which are banned worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The move came three weeks after the government embargoed the
imports and sell of those tuna products contaminated by the
soybeans which may cause malfunction of genes of the consumers.
</P>
<P>
Local daily Al-ektissadiya on Sunday quoted market sources as
saying that more than 70 percent of tuna sold in the Saudi markets
come from Thailand, which is regarded as the world's biggest tuna
exporter.
</P>
<P>
An official at the Saudi Ministry of Commerce expected that
millions of packages of tuna will be confiscated due to a large
stock of tuna during this period. 
</P>
