<HEADLINE> Philippine President Brushes Off Coup Rumors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
Sunday brushed aside coup rumors and said that the military is
solidly behind him.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Cebu before leaving for
Manila following a four-day visit to Eastern and Central Visayas,
Estrada said that the speculations of a coup over this weekend
were a figment of the imagination of his political foes.
</P>
<P>
"You can ask major commands of the military if they ever think
of having a coup. It's only imaginary, a figment of the
imagination of those people who lost in the last elections," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada also said that former President Corazon Aquino has
assured him of her cooperation with his administration.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said he does not believe "Mrs. Aquino is behind a
supposed Silent Protest Movement against the administration."
</P>
<P>
"I was with President Aquino yesterday afternoon. We heard mass
together, and she assured me of her cooperation and help in (my)
undertakings," Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada told his followers to refrain from being engaged in a
battle of stickers to counter the criticism of his detractors.
</P>
<P>
Personalities linked to the Aquino administration have been
reportedly carrying out a sticker campaign against the Estrada
administration.
</P>
<P>
Calling their movement the "Silent Protest," they placed
stickers (with an exclamation mark) on vehicles and other property
to show their opposition to the president.
</P>
<P>
"I have nothing to do with that. Maybe some of our followers
are just answering those stickers. But I told them to stop it. We
should not give any importance to stickers," the president said.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, one local newspaper said that right wing soldiers
were planning a coup over this weekend to overthrow the Estrada
government. But the rumor was dismissed by government and military
officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
