<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing Encourages "Tree Funerals" to Save Farmland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- To protect cropland against
encroachment by graves, the Civil Affairs Bureau of this
Municipality in southwest China has been encouraging local people
to adopt "tree funerals", that is, to bury the ashes of their
loved ones and plant trees on them.
</P>
<P>
Zeng Guangming, an official with the bureau, said that to bury
the ashes of the deceased under trees or lawns will not only help
to save farmland, but also help to beautify the environment.
</P>
<P>
Relatives of the deceased only need to pay 500 yuan as a
management fee. They can choose whether to bury the ashes of their
loved ones under trees or under lawns. The departments in charge
of memorial parks will determine what kind of trees will be
planted.
</P>
<P>
Memorial trees will be owned by the relatives of the deceased
for 20 years, Zeng said.
</P>
<P>
Already, 300 families have used this method to pay their
respects to their loved ones, according to Zeng.
</P>
<P>
"Tree funerals" are new concepts for Chinese people, who
traditionally prefer interment in coffins with large tomb mounds
erected over them, Zeng said.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing has a population of 31 million, and about 200,000
people pass away each year. If all the deceased were to be buried,
the municipality would have to set aside more than 133 hectares of
farmland every year, Zeng said. He pointed out that the city's
current amount of cultivated land stands at 2.25 million hectares,
much lower than the national level.
</P>
<P>
China's first funeral reform came in 1956, when the late
Chairman Mao Zedong and 150 other central and provincial
government officials agreed to cremation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
