<HEADLINE> Shanghai Launches Wildlife Protection Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A campaign was launched today in
this east China metropolis, with the aim of educating its
residents in the importance of protecting wildlife.
</P>
<P>
Jointly sponsored by several organizations, including the
Shanghai Municipal Wildlife Conservation Association and the
international Wildlife Conservation Society (WCS), the campaign
sprang from a proposal by eight scientists and a local student-
sponsored wildlife protection club, calling on the 13 million
residents of Shanghai to combat the practice of killing and eating
protected species.
</P>
<P>
Poaching and trading in wild animals are still rampant
worldwide, despite intensified efforts by the international
community to ban such activities, according to an official from
the WCS, who added that trading in wildlife has become rampant in
recent years, becoming the third-largest illegal trade next to
drugs and weapons.
</P>
<P>
China is faced with a grim challenge in protecting its wildlife,
since it has to protect 156 endangered species from extinction,
out of over 640 endangered species internationally, noted
biologist Yang Xiongli said.
</P>
<P>
"Every animal species represents a unique gene bank of
immeasurable value," Yang said. He also expressed his outrage at
the widespread practice in China of eating rare species of animals
such as swans and peacocks.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai alone, about 1,000 tons of snakes are eaten
annually, he said.
</P>
<P>
The campaign for wildlife protection is expected to last eight
months, highlighted by various forms of public education
activities, competitions and exhibitions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
