<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Enact New Bill on Securities, Futures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region will exact new regulations on securities and
futures, said a senior official today.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong needs a modern regulatory framework for the
securities and futures market to enhance its competitiveness as an
international financial center and the prime capital formation
center for the mainland, said Rafael Hui, Secretary for Financial
Services, at the launching ceremony for a three-month consultation
drive on the Securities and Futures Bill.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from consolidating ten existing ordinances, we have
introduced new measures in the Bill to simplify certain regulatory
arrangements to reduce compliance burden, close existing
regulatory gaps in order to promote market confidence, enhance
investor protection, reduce market misconduct and systemic risks,
and facilitate innovation and competition," Hui said.
</P>
<P>
Major new regulatory measures include the introduction of a
single license for market intermediaries to streamline regulatory
arrangements and bring in new licensing requirements to enhance
protection of clients' assets and the establishment of a civil
Market Misconduct Tribunal and expanding the existing criminal
route to combat market misconduct.
</P>
<P>
The disclosure regime for more timely dissemination of price-
sensitive information will be modernized to enable investors to
make better informed decisions, and the new bill will help
investors seek compensation by creating specific private causes of
action against market misconduct and false disclosure of
information.
</P>
<P>
A flexible framework for the regulation of automated trading
services will be introduced to facilitate market innovation.
</P>
<P>
"The government accords top priority in preparing the
Securities and Futures Bill to meet this competitive challenge,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"The bill, which seeks to meet the 21st century requirements of
our market and the users, is now ready for the public to comment,"
the secretary said.
</P>
<P>
The Securities and Futures Bill is published in the form of a
White Bill for a three-month consultation, as announced by the
Financial Secretary in his Budget Speech on March 8.
</P>
<P>
It will establish a regulatory framework for the development of
a fair, orderly and transparent market that is on a par with
international standards and practices, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
