at the U.N.
</P>
<P>
Environmental Program headquarters in Kenya's capital Nairobi,
to review the trade bans on elephants, whales and other endangered
species.
</P>
<P>
Biwott said Kenya has put forward a proposal urging all parties
to be aware of the possible repercussion to their tourism
industries growth when making decision relating to trade in
wildlife products.
</P>
<P>
Kenya Wildlife Service noted that commercial trade on wildlife
products has contributed to the decline of wild animals and
plants, saying the forthcoming Cites meeting is important to
African countries since they hold the largest number of wildlife
in the world. 
