<HEADLINE> Zambian President Disappointed With Congo Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick Chiluba
has expressed disappointment with the Democratic Republic of the
Congo (DRC) on the continued violations of the Lusaka Peace
agreement signed last July.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba was speaking at the Lusaka International Airport on
Sunday shortly before his departure to Cairo, Egypt, where he is
scheduled to attend a two-day European-African summit.
</P>
<P>
He observed that when signatories concerned met at the Security
Council of the United Nations in January this year, they all
re-affirmed their commitment to the Lusaka Peace process.
</P>
<P>
He added that another meeting was convened in Lusaka for all
parties concerned to reaffirm their commitment shortly after the
Security Council meeting.
</P>
<P>
The President however observed that there were factors which
could have led to violations of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
"Firstly we expected the observer team from the U.N. to be in
immediately."
</P>
<P>
"Their absence to me creates a vacuum and people take advantage
of this."
</P>
<P>
But one also has to understand that the observer team is not
armed and they wanted to be sure that there would be security and
they would be allowed access both by the government and to whoever
holds territory in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
The President said all parties involved in the peace process
were eager to see peace return to that country adding that they
would not give up.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that signatories come back to realization
since nobody had the capacity to continue in the war.
</P>
<P>
"We need money for development and not fighting. I only hope
signatories will come back to realization," he said.
</P>
<P>
And commenting on the two-day European-African summit, Chiluba
said details on the new relationship would emerge later.
</P>
<P>
He observed that there had been such a relationship which had
been going on for sometime but added that this seemed to be
entering a new phase where Europe and Africa wished to establish
stronger ties both economically and politically. 
</P>
</TEXT>
