<HEADLINE> Olympic Tourists Warned of Drowning Dangers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Olympic tourists from all over
the world might face another danger during their tour of the
Sydney Games -- dangerous surf at beaches.
</P>
<P>
A total of 305 people drowned in Australia in the 12 months
from July 1998 to June 1999, according to figures from the Royal
Life Saving Society of Australia.
</P>
<P>
Surf Life Saving Australia (SLSA) national medical officer
Peter Fenner said a fifth of people drowned in Australia were
tourists who died within four days of arrival at the country.
</P>
<P>
Fenner said SLSA had failed to encourage airlines to screen
multilingual videos warning visitors of the dangers of the surf.
He held that hotels at beaches should employ lifeguards and more
beach patrols should be paid.
</P>
<P>
The largest single cause of drowning nationwide was rips, or
strong currents, which drag people out to sea. Even many of the
competitors from 38 countries and regions at recent the life-
saving world championships at Manly beach cannot identify a the
dangerous surf, Fenner added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
