<HEADLINE> OAU Chief Says Africa Ready For New Chapter With Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the Organization

of African Unity (OAU) salem Ahmad salem said on Sunday that
Africa is ready to turn a new leaf in relations with Europe.
</P>
<P>
Salem made the remarks on the fringe of the preparatory meetings

for the Africa-Europe summit due on Monday and Tuesday, adding that
Europe is Africa's prime partner despite the fact that there are
some differences in the views of the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that in the new century and the new millennium, we
start a dialog that rests on cooperation and views equally the
interests of the two sides," he said.
</P>
<P>
Africa has its apprehensions regarding the issue of debts, he
said. If the issue of African debts was not seriously settled,
efforts of the continent to effect economic and political reforms
will be futile, he stresses.
</P>
<P>
The combined external debts of African countries have reached
350 billion U.S. dollars, accounting for 93 percent of the whole
African gross domestic product and severely hindering the
development of the continent.
</P>
<P>
On the issues of democratization and human rights which are
always raised by Europe, he said that Africa has adopted one
stance in this regard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
