back to negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Defense Minister Ghazi Zuetir said on Friday his
country would ask Syria, the major power broker of Lebanon, to send
troops to south Lebanon after Israel's unilateral withdrawal from
its self-styled security zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
However, Lebanese officials said it was Zuetir's personal point
of view.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a self-proclaimed 15-kilometer-deep security
zone in 1985 in south Lebanon with a claimed aim of protecting its
northern border from cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
Last month Israeli cabinet approved Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
plan to pullout its troops from south Lebanon with or without a
peace agreement with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, which stations some 35,000 troops in Lebanon,
have insisted on the simultaneity of their peace talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Damascus has been demanding that Israel commit to a full
withdrawal from the strategic Golan Heights it captured from Syria
in the 1967 Mideast war back to the June 4, 1967 border lines,
while Israel has rejected the Syrian demands.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish state is keen to maintain full control of access to
the Sea of Galilee, the main source of fresh water for Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian peace talks, which resumed last December in
Washington after a four-year hiatus, were suspended in January
after two rounds of talks in the U.S. failed to solve the thorny
issue of the fate of the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
However, both sides have said the door is still open for further
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss is scheduled to visit
Damascus on Sunday for further talks with Syria on the peace
process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
