<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel not to Allow Northern Border Under Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Israel will not allow any foreign
troop deployment over its northern border that threatens its
unilateral withdrawal from south Lebanon, Israeli military sources
said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Any foreign troop deployment over Israel's northern border would
be regarded by Israel as an infringement of the "red lines" between
Israeli and Syrian troops in Lebanon, the sources told Israel
Radio.
</P>
<P>
The military sources made these remarks while commenting on the
Lebanese Defense Minister Ghazi Zaiter's statement on Saturday that
Beirut may ask Syrian troops to deploy in south Lebanon after
Israel's pullout there.
</P>
<P>
If israel withdraws unilaterally from the security zone, "this
raises the possibility to the Lebanese government to ask Syria to
send its troops to the south with the Lebanese army," Zaiter was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Zaiter said he wanted to make it clear that his statement is
just his personal opinion and not Lebanon's official policy,
adding "the aim of such a request is not to make Syria protect
Israeli northern borders, but to put Tel Aviv in the range of the
Syrian rockets."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Zaiter's statement, Danny Naveh, who heads the
Likud's reaction team, said Sunday that Israel must be tough and
must demand a total withdrawal of Syrian troops from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Syria would at this stage sit on the sideline in Lebanon and
avoid a direct confrontation with Israel, Tourism Minister Amnon
Lipkin-Shahak said Sunday, adding that "were Syrians to sit on the
Lebanese border, this would create a whole new situation."
</P>
<P>
Justice Minister Yossi Beilin said Saturday night that Zaiter's
statement reflects the tragedy of Lebanese-Syrian relations, and
that any new developments in southern Lebanon after Israel's
withdrawal should be carefully monitored by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Chief of General Staff of the Israel Defense Force Lt-Gen. Shaul
Mofaz is to brief the cabinet Sunday on the situation in southern
Lebanon and on preparations under way for the July withdrawal which
has been approved by the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Israel expects the withdrawal to take place in the context of U.
N. Security Council Resolution 425, which calls for the deployment
of either Lebanese or international forces on the border.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Ehud Barak has said that if Israel is attacked
from Lebanon after the withdrawal, Israel will not hesitate to
retaliate.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the security zone in south Lebanon in 1985 with a
self-proclaimed purpose of protecting its northern security.
</P>
</TEXT>
