<HEADLINE> Clinton, Arafat to Meet in Washington Later This Month: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat will hold a summit meeting later
this month in Washington, the Voice of Palestine radio reported on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The summit, which the U.S. proposed to be held on April 26, will
discuss the outcome of an upcoming session of the Palestinian-
Israeli talks slated for Thursday and ways of boosting ties between
the U.S. and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
Thursday's session will be followed by a new round of talks
should the two sides reach an agreement on all issues related to
the last stage of Israeli troops redeployment in the West Bank and
the final status, Hassan Abdel Rahman, the Palestine Liberation
Organization's envoy to Washington was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
After the Syrian-U.S. summit, recently held in Geneva, failed to
set the stalled Syrian-Israeli negotiations in motion, the U.S.
administration said it plans to exert more efforts very soon to
push forward the Palestinian track so as to enable the two sides to
reach a final peace treaty by the September deadline.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinians have set a May deadline to draft a
framework agreement on the thorny issues, including the fate of
Jerusalem, the return of Palestinian refugees, borders and water
issues, in order to reach a final peace treaty by September.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Clinton had met in Washington in January to nudge
Israel and the Palestinians to reach a framework agreement on
final-status issues before the February 13 deadline under the Sharm
el Sheikh Memorandum signed last September.
</P>
<P>
The two sides failed to meet the February deadline due to
differences over the areas to be transferred to the Palestinians in
the third stage redeployment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
