<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Spots New Cases of Vesicular Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 2 (Xinhua) -- South Korea Sunday began to take
measures to prevent the spread of vesicular disease among
livestock in Hongsong County, South Chungchong Province as scores
of heads of cattle and pigs there were found infected with the
disease.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry has banned exit of
people, vehicles and livestock from the infected areas in Hongsong
and slaughtered 58 heads of cattle and 35 pigs within 500 meter
radius from a farm where the cases were spotted.
</P>
<P>
The disease, which causes blisters on the mouth and hoof of
livestock, was first discovered last Monday and killed dozens of
livestock in Paju, Kyonggi Province in the country.
</P>
<P>
The ministry ruled out the possibility that the vesicular
disease in Hongsong was contaminated by the cases in Paju, saying
that the cases were found in Hongsong almost concurrently with
those in Paju, which was declared by the South Korean government
as quasi-disaster area last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the livestock in Paju which had blisters in feet, cattle
and pigs in Hongsong did not have blisters in their feet.
</P>
<P>
Japan and China's Taiwan have suspended import of livestock and
meat from South Korea while the United States and Australia halted
import of dairy products from the country although the vesicular
disease is harmless to humans.
</P>
<P>
Kim Ok-kyoung, director of South Korean Quarantine Department,
said Sunday the analysis of the blisters, viruses, blood serum and
saliva from the dead livestock showed the disease is an O-type
epidemic on livestock's mouth and hoof which swept Taiwan one year
ago.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that the epidemic was found in the Korean
peninsula after 1934. Enidtem
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
