<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Assures Tanzania of No New Refugee Flow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government has
assured Tanzania that the political adjustments occurring in the
country would not result into any major disorder that might
reactivate the flow of refugees to Tanzania, media here reported
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the situation in Rwanda following the resignation of
 President Pasteur Bizimungu, the Rwandan Ambassador to Tanzania
Zephyr Mutanguha stressed in Dar es Salaam on Saturday the recent
changes would not lead to any kind of conflict and there was
nothing to fear as the changes were supported by a majority of
Rwanda citizens, political parties, and other organizations.
</P>
<P>
The recent changes in Rwanda have not caused instability as
feared by many people, the Rwandan envoy was quoted as saying by
the Sunday Observer newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda was determined to build a strong and stable political
and economical structure. This is what it has learned from long
experience of the recurring conflicts in the country, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Bizimungu resigned from power about a fortnight ago, leaving
behind an atmosphere of uncertainty following his strong
allegations against the parliament and the government before his
abrupt resignation.
</P>
<P>
The Ambassador said Bizimungu's resignation was a new chapter
in Rwandan history, as it marked the first time that a serving
president had left office without any blood being shed.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that there was a legal and democratic process in
place in his country to ensure that the interim period was
peaceful.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the move toward electing a new president
within 30 days after the resignation was already under way as the
ruling party, the Rwandan Patriotic Front (RPF), was expected to
meet almost immediately to nominate presidential candidates who
would later be forwarded to the parliament for sanctioning.
</P>
<P>
Triggered by a bloody civil war which broke out in April 1994,
an estimated 170,000 Rwandan refugees entered the neighboring
Tanzania within 48 hours on April 28 and 29 of 1994, making the
biggest refugee influx never before witnessed in the history of
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are around 7,600 Rwandan refugees staying in
Tanzania's northwestern Kigoma and Kagera refugee camps
established by the UN High Commissioner for Refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
