<HEADLINE> Defense Pact Between Nigeria And United States Ruled Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Visiting United States Secretary of
Defense, William Cohen, Saturday ruled out the possibility of a
defense pact between his country and Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
But he said in Nigeria's capital Abuja after meeting with
President Olusegun Obasanjo and Defense Minister, Lt.-Gen.
Theophilus Danjuma, that the United States is to spend 10 million
U.S. dollars on the Nigerian military establishment to make it
thoroughly professional.
</P>
<P>
The defense secretary's pronouncement has put to rest reports
that Nigeria was angling for a defense cooperation agreement with
the United States, the Guardian newspaper reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Some legislators at the National Assembly had earlier moved a
motion for a U.S-Nigeria military pact as the only way to keep
ambitious soldiers from usurping power and safeguard the country's
nascent democracy, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
Fielding questions at a press conference, Cohen said the idea
of a military pact was not on the agenda of his visit, stressing
that the only way to forestall coups is to have "strict civilian
control over the military".
</P>
<P>
According to him, the essence of his delegation's presence in
Nigeria is to strengthen existing military ties, consolidate on
military reforms and to "sustain the bond of democracy in
Nigeria."
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. will assist Nigeria in its peace-keeping
effort in Africa "because we recognize Nigeria as an important
country in Africa considering the leadership role she has been
playing in various dimensions."
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
