<HEADLINE> UN Earmarks US$13 Million for Tanzania's Road Maintenance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Two UN organizations have
allocated more than 13 million U.S. dollars for rehabilitation and
maintenance of district and feeder roads in Tanzania's northwest
Mwanza Region.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Sunday News, the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) and the UN Capital Development Fund
(UNCDF) will also use the money to finance social economic
infrastructure projects as part of a five-year poverty alleviation
strategy being implemented in the region.
</P>
<P>
Under a sustainable human development program carried out
jointly with the Tanzania government, UNDP was utilizing
labor-based engineers, private contractors, consultants and
district engineers in the maintenance of feeder roads.
</P>
<P>
In phase one of the program that started in 1998, engineers,
technicians and road inspectors had been trained and several field
and office equipment had been purchased.
</P>
<P>
The second phase has started this year with projects being
implemented in several districts of the region. 
</P>
