<DOCNO> XIE20000402.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Spends Huge Sum of Money on Curbing Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai has spent 32.8 billion
yuan (3.95 billion U.S. dollars) to curb industrial pollution over
the past decade, turning 80 percent of the former polluting
enterprises into clean ones.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, the biggest industrial city of China has completed
more than 3,600 pollution control projects and more than 330 waste
treatment projects and closed down 56 severely polluting companies.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the amount of industrial waste water in 1999
dropped by 5.6 percent from the previous year as the local economy
grew by over 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
This year, the city will continue to resolve problems of the
110 enterprises that have been listed as major pollution sources
in the city. It will close down or move these enterprises out of
the city.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
