<HEADLINE> Blazers Beat Bucks on Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Milwaukee Bucks were dealt
a heavy blow to make the postseason as they were whitewashed 79-
113 by the Portland Trail Blazers on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Damon Stoudamire scored his season-high 31 points to send the
Bucks their worst loss of the season, and slipped 2 1/2 games
behind Orlando and Detroit in the battle for the final two Eastern
Conference playoff spots.
</P>
<P>
Stoudamire matched Terry Porter's franchise record by burying
seven 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
Sam Cassell scored 22 points for Milwaukee but All-Star Ray
Allen managed only 13 and Glenn Robinson was held to just nine.
</P>
<P>
In Chicago, Elden Campbell scored 25 points and Eddie Jones
added 23, including two free throws with 3.8 seconds left, as the
Charlotte Hornets edged the Bulls 90-87 to post their sixth
straight victory.
</P>
<P>
The fifth-place Hornets moved just one game behind Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
In Denver, Antonio McDyess had 33 points and Nick Van Exel
scored 27 points to lead the Nuggets to a 112-92 victory over Utah
Jazz who was playing for the third time in four nights.
</P>
<P>
Karl Malone led Utah with 27 points and 13 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
In Cleveland, Shawn Kemp scored 22 points and Cedric Henderson
added 20 off the bench to lead the Cavaliers to a 109-103 victory
over the Boston Celtics.
</P>
<P>
The Celtics have dropped seven in row to see their postseason
hopes evaporate as they slipped seven games behind eighth-place
Orlando.
</P>
<P>
In Houston, rookie Kenny Thomas scored 18 points and grabbed a
season-high 22 rebounds to lead the Rockets to a 115-93 rout of
the hapless Atlanta Hawks. 
</P>
