<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Nuclear Fuel Element Plant Breaks Ground </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The first nuclear fuel element
plant in China broke ground Saturday in Baotou City in north China
's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region which is expected to provide
fuel elements for a nuclear power station in east China.
</P>
<P>
Two more heavy-water reactors are under construction in
Qingshan in east China's Zhejiang Province now with an installed
generating capacity of 700,000 kilowatts each.
</P>
<P>
The two heavy-water reactors are expected to first use imported
nuclear fuel elements provided by the Canadian government, which
will then be replaced by China-made nuclear fuel elements starting
from 2003.
</P>
<P>
The new nuclear fuel elements plant is of great political and
strategic importance since it will ensure stable fuel elements
supply for the country's nuclear power stations, according to an
official with the China Nuclear Industrial Group.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear fuel element plant is expected to go into trial
production in September 2001, and start to provide fuel elements
for Qingshan Nuclear Power Station in March 2003.
</P>
<P>
With a projected investment of 200 million yuan, the plant is
designed to produce 200 tons of nuclear fuel elements annually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
