<HEADLINE> Report: Estrada Asked Not to Go on Long Foreign Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
has been advised against going on long overseas trips in the face
of a spreading opposition movement and rumors of a possible coup
attempt,Philippine Daily Inquirer said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted presidential palace sources as saying
presidential advisers are concerned over President Estrada's
scheduled state visits to foreign countries, including Britain and
France, because of the emergence of the so-called "Silent Protest"
Movement seeking his eventual ouster.
</P>
<P>
The advisers also said Estrada's domestic travels are also
going to be "minimized" because of recent intelligence reports
about an alleged assassination attempt, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
However, the military said Saturday that rumors of a weekend
coup against Estrada were the "biggest April Fool's Day joke," and
that rumor mongers could be charged.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado also dismissed the rumors as
coffee-shop talk.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Manila Standard newspaper reported Sunday that
the military has placed under tight surveillance four persons,
including two newspaper columnists, allegedly for fanning rumors
of a coup over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Although it brushed off the coup rumors, the military has been
placed on red alert since last week and security at military camps
and other strategic targets have been strengthened, the Philippine
Star newspaper said Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
