"I am optimistic the ministries responsible for the
implementation of the 42 items will complete their tasks right on
time," Coordinating Minister for Economy, Finance and Industry
Kwik Kian Gie said.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the government must complete the
implementation of some 42 key economic measures as a prerequisite
for the disbursement of 400 million U.S. dollars in bailout funds
from the IMF.
</P>
<P>
He did not elaborate on these 42 economic measures, but said
they particularly focus on bank and corporate restructuring
programs.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government signed a letter of intent with the
IMF on January 20, in which it promised to complete a host of
ambitious economic measures by the end of March.
</P>
<P>
But many of the key programs were not completed by the deadline,
prompting the IMF to delay the disbursement of the 400 million
dollars, which had been scheduled for April 4.
</P>
<P>
The money is part of a 5 billion dollars loan package promised
in January by the IMF to finance the country's economic reform
programs.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, President Abdurrahman Wahid forbade his ministers
to travel overseas until they reach an agreement with the IMF on a
new deadline.
</P>
<P>
Minister Gie said the IMF is now expected to disburse part of
the loan in May.
</P>
<P>
He added that the delay in the disbursement of the IMF money
has no significant impact on the government's finances, but
stressed that the completion of the economic reforms is crucial to
reviving confidence in the ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
"Our balance of payment is adequate for the next six months,"
he was quoted by The Jakarta Post Sunday as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
