<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Condensed Water" First Found in Taklimakan Desert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have found that
there exists "condensed water" in the Taklimakan Desert of the
northwest Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Scientists Wang Hong, Li Fenglin from the Geology and Minerals
Institute of Tianjin made the discovery when they were exploring
waters in the dry land.
</P>
<P>
Also called "suspended water", the "condensed water" is
believed to come into shape when evaporated water from the water-
able aquifer meets cold air at the ground surface of the desert.
</P>
<P>
Geologists first put out the theory in the mid 20th century
that there exist natural "condensed water". However, it has not
been proved until now.
</P>
<P>
The two scientists found the "condensed water" at two sites
around the place named "Tazhong".
</P>
<P>
One site was located at the halfway of a small sand dune. The
water at the site disappeared two days later together with the wet
sand.
</P>
<P>
About half a month later, they discovered another site in the
middle of a sand dune a wet 2.5-meter-long, one-meter-wide wet
sand belt.
</P>
<P>
The Taklimakan Desert has long been nicknamed as the "dead sea"
where no plant or grass can exist.
</P>
<P>
The discovery of "condensed water" in the desert has proved
that there exists water in the shallow underground of the desert.
</P>
<P>
"This will bring much benefits to the future development of the
desert," Wang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000402.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Suffers Capital Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Capital flight from Venezuela last
year reached 4.6 billion U.S. dollars, the Economic and Financial
Counseling Office (OAEF) said in a report released on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The advisory body, which is affiliated to the congress of the
country, said the exit of capital conforms to the dynamics between
the rates of interest on banking documents in bolivars, the
country's currency, the rates of interest paid by deposits abroad,
and the money depreciation expected.
</P>
<P>
The relation between these variables has encouraged the exit of
capital in search of bigger profits.
</P>
<P>
It said that the lack of a consistent economic program of
medium and long term, together with the lack of incentives to
private investments, generates doubts about the sustainability of
an eventual growth powered by public funds.
</P>
<P>
"These factors have affected the confidence of investors, who
used their capital to seek hard currency, and if the trend
continues unchecked, the flight of capital will go on during the
year 2000," it noted.
</P>
<P>
The flight of capital occurs despite the extraordinary growth
of 19 percent in the value of oil exports compared to 1998 and a
drop of imports of 21 percent from 1998 to 1999, it added.
</P>
<P>
Foreign reserves closed at 16 billion dollars this weekend, a
drop of 94 million dollars as against the same period of the
previous year, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
