<HEADLINE> Secrete Tunnel Found in Colombian Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Colombian authorities Saturday
uncovered a 70-meter-long clandestine tunnel in the La Modelo
prison of Bogota which could be used for a mass escape.
</P>
<P>
The yard where the digging of the tunnel was started was shared
by the offenders from the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (
FARC), the National Liberation Army (ELN) rebels, as well as
common criminals, said the prison head warden, Lieutenant Reynaldo
Fierro.
</P>
<P>
The interns included people accused of the assassination of
former presidential candidate for the Conservative Party Alvaro
Gomez Hurtado and those who killed journalist and humorist Jaime
Garzon, added Fierro.
</P>
<P>
Others were the alleged perpetrators of the attack against
lawyer Antonio Cansicon who defended former president Ernesto
Samper during the scandal about the supposed contribution of drug
money to his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
Fierro said he couldn't attribute the building of the tunnel to
anyone else or any other groups jailed in the yard of the prison
housing some 1,200 inmates.
</P>
<P>
The authorities, who seized charts of the prison and compasses,
said that the tunnel started in an empty cell and ended in a sewer
close to the Attorney General Office in the west of the city.
</P>
<P>
Police and army forces surrounded the prison to prevent
possible unrest after the discovery of the tunnel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
