<HEADLINE> Colombian Ethnic Indians Protest Government Petroleum Permit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- About 1,200 Indians of the Uwa
community of Colombia occupied Cubara in the Andea region of
Boyaca to demand the government cancel the license granted to
Occidental Petroleum (Oxy) to explore the area adjacent to the
Indian settlement, the ethnic group said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Uwa spokesman Fabio Tegria said that it is "a peaceful
occupation of undefined duration" to protest the government's
granting to the multinational Oxy an environmental permit to
explore the Samore block next to the Uwa reservation in Boyaca.
</P>
<P>
The occupation, which aimed to force the oil company to leave
the region, some 250 kilometers northeast of Bogota, occurred
despite a judge's order to suspend the exploration in reply to a
demand filed by the aboriginal community to reclaim its
fundamental rights.
</P>
<P>
The Uwa opposes oil exploitation because their beliefs consider
crude as the blood of the earth.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Colombian Oil Company (Ecopetrol) chairman Alberto
Calderon Zuleta said that the Samore bloc has reserves close to
three billion barrels and its exploitation is indispensable to
maintain crude production and avoid imports.
</P>
<P>
Calderon said although the oil enterprise respects the judicial
decision, it will appeal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
