<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Education News in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The following is a review of major
education stories Xinhua released from March 26 to April 1:
</P>
<P>
 Chinese, Foreign Educators Discuss Teaching Reform
</P>
<P>
Nearly 30 Chinese and foreign educators gathered in Beijing
from March 27 to 31 to discuss reforming the teaching of science
and technology at primary and secondary levels, as well as child
development in the new century.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, co-sponsored by the Ministry of Education, the
United Nations International Bureau of Education, and United
Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization, is
focusing on the difficulties faced by many countries in their
attempts to make such reforms and on exploring ways for
improvements.
</P>
<P>
 MOE to Increase Assistance to University Students
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Education recently worked out a plan to
increase subsidies to university and college students from poor
families to discourage them from dropping out of school, according
to a national education work conference held on March 28 in Xi'an,
Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
As of the end of last year, almost 10,000 students from 54
schools, in eight pilot cities, had signed agreements on borrowing
student loans, totaling 400 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Loans to Help Poor College Students
</P>
<P>
China's financially strapped college students will now be able
to complete their studies without worrying about money, said a
Ministry of Education official on March 29.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Education and Ministry of Finance issued a
notice last year asking colleges to spend 10 percent of student
tuition fees to provide poor students with part-time jobs to help
them complete their studies.
</P>
<P>
Also, at the beginning of last autumn's term, an experimental
loan system for needy students was introduced which allows a 50
percent discount on interest and a four year grace period after
graduation for repayment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
