<DOCNO> XIE20000402.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (1)  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are highlights of
major environment stories Xinhua released from March 26 to April 1:
</P>
<P>
 Huge Lake Reappears at "Mountain of Flames"
</P>
<P>
A huge lake recently reappeared near the "Mountain of Flames"
at Turpan Basin, the driest area in China, perhaps in the world.
</P>
<P>
The lake, 10 kilometers long and three km in width, was filled
with water from underground percolation, and melted mountain snow
and glacier ice.
</P>
<P>
Located about 60 km southeast of Urumqi, capital of northwest
China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, the lake is 161 meters
below the sea level, the world's second-lowest lake after the Dead
Sea in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The lake is a rebirth of Aiding Lake, which dried up a decade
ago as the result of evaporation and excessive use of water in the
region.
</P>
<P>
"The reappearance of the lake can be attributed to more
flooding than in normal years, replenishment of 100 million cubic
meters of underground water, and, more importantly, popularization
of water-saving techniques in developing agriculture over the past
years," said Bai Jianjun, director of Turpan City Bureau of Water
Resources.
</P>
<P>
China's Giant Pandas Waiting to Be Adopted
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement signed recently between the China
Wildlife Conservation Association (CWCA) and the twinbays.com, an
America-based e-commerce website, China will start from April 1 to
raise funds on line to protect giant pandas.
</P>
<P>
Five giant pandas from the Wolong Nature Reserve in southwest
China's Sichuan Province will be adopted under the fund-raising
program, said CWCA secretary-general Wang Fuxing.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first time that China goes on line to raise
funds for the protection of wildlife, he said.
</P>
<P>
Use of Tiger Parts to Cure Disease Endangering Tigers
</P>
<P>
The tradition to make medicine with tiger parts including the
bones remains a leading threat to tigers, according to a report
released Thursday by TRAFFIC, a wild animal protection
organization.
</P>
<P>
The trade in tiger skins and curios is also threatening the
existence of the big cats, with a population of no more than 8,000
across the world.
</P>
<P>
Tiger-bone medicines and tonics have been used as a treatment
for rheumatism and related ailments for thousands of years in Asia
and people will try to obtain them, even at some risk, said the
report by the Trade Records Analysis of Flora and Fauna in
Commerce (TRAFFIC).
</P>
<P>
The report, titled Far From A Cure: The Tiger Trade Revisited,
warned that the fight to save the tiger risks being lost if
conservationists become complacent with the advances made in the
1990s towards reducing use of tiger bone in traditional Asian
medicine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000402.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (2)  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China will launch its third national giant panda survey
starting in April, said Ma Fu, deputy director of the State
Forestry Administration.
</P>
<P>
The survey will determine the number of giant pandas living in
the wild, in zoos and their habitats. This information will
facilitate setting up a giant panda monitoring system and
information management system, said Ma.
</P>
<P>
The survey will include 55 counties in southwest China's
Sichuan Province and northwestern Shaanxi and Gansu provinces,
covering an area of more than 22 million hectares.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that only 1,000 giant pandas survive in the
mountainous regions of Sichuan, Shaanxi and Gansu provinces. To
protect the endangered animal, China has set up 33 nature reserves,
covering a total area of 1.6 million hectares.
</P>
<P>
 Grain-for-Green Project Takes off in West China
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has started a 1.9-billion-yuan grain-for-
green project in China's western region.
</P>
<P>
China has unveiled a detailed plan of grain aid to the western
region.
</P>
<P>
According to a notice issued by the State Forestry
Administration, the State Development Planning Commission and the
Ministry of Finance, farmers in the west will receive subsidies in
the form of grain after they turn cultivated land into forest and
pasture.
</P>
<P>
The project will turn more than 340,000 hectares of cultivated
land back to forest and more than 430,000 hectares of bare
mountains and lands in western China.
</P>
<P>
 Chongqing to Invest More in Liquid Sewage Treatment
</P>
<P>
This municipality of Chongqing in southwest China is to
allocate three billion yuan (about 361 million US dollars) in the
coming four years to carry out new sewage treatment projects, in a
bid to control growing environmental pollution in its urban areas.
</P>
<P>
The planned investment is equal to the total investment in this
aspect over the past dozens of years.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing, one of the country's economic giants, has urban
sewage treatment plants which currently can only handle a total of
5,040 tons of liquid sewage per day, 6.3 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the city has set a goal to have 80 percent of its
urban liquid sewage treated by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2004, the city will have six large urban sewage
treatment plants and a 75-km long sewage transfer pipe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000402.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (3)  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chongqing Municipality in northwest China plans to invest 10
billion yuan (1.2 billion U.S. dollars) to improve the ecological
environment in the coming ten years, officials said today.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, Chongqing will turn 183,300 ha of low-
yield farmland on slopes of mountains into forests and grassland,
take good care of the existing 2.3 million ha of forest resources,
and plant trees and grass in 1.06 million ha of wasteland.
</P>
<P>
When the work is finished in 2010, the city's vegetation
coverage rate will increase from 23 percent at present to 36
percent.
</P>
<P>
As part of the ambitious ten-year plan, the city will also make
great effort to ban unauthorized reclamation and logging, and
crack down illegal wood trading.
</P>
<P>
 Chinese Vice Premier Urges Quicker Greening
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Premier Wen Jiabao said at a plenary meeting of
the National Greening Committee (NGC) held in Beijing last week
that the country will continue to push forward the campaign of all
the people volunteering to plant trees.
</P>
<P>
Wen, also director of the NGC, said that the country should
also accelerate afforestation in both urban and rural areas,
improve ecological environment and conditions of agriculture and
coordinate afforestation efforts with the implementation of the
national strategy of developing the western part of China.
</P>
<P>
He said that many green corridors should be developed across
the country and various key ecological projects should be
accelerated.
</P>
<P>
In order to improve the quality of afforestation, he said that
the country has to strengthen management, rely on technology,
improve relevant mechanism, strengthen enforcement of laws and
improve leadership in this respect.
</P>
<P>
China Develops Eco-Agriculture
</P>
<P>
China has made substantial achievements in eco-agriculture in
the past two decades, according to a national conference on eco-
farming.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the first day of the conference, the vice-minister
of agriculture, Zhang Baowen, said that in the early 1980s China
initiated experiments in eco-farming to deal with the situation of
deteriorating environment.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, several central government departments formed a
national leading group on eco-agriculture and set up 51 state-
level eco-agriculture pilot counties. Over six billion yuan has
been invested in the pilots counties, generating about 13.7
billion yuan. Local farmers have benefited a lot from the projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
