<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2100GMT, Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel will not allow any foreign troop deployment
over its northern border that threatens its unilateral withdrawal
from south Lebanon, Israeli military sources said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Any foreign troop deployment over Israel's northern border would
be regarded by Israel as an infringement of the "red lines" between
Israeli and Syrian troops in Lebanon, the sources told Israel
Radio.
</P>
<P>
The military sources made these remarks while commenting on the
Lebanese Defense Minister Ghazi Zaiter's statement on Saturday that
Beirut may ask Syrian troops to deploy in south Lebanon after
Israel's pullout there. (Israel-Lebanon)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Visiting Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh Sunday
denied the saying that Syria would pour into south Lebanon after
Israel's withdrawal, People's Voice radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Shareh has delivered a message from Syrian President Hafez Assad
to Lebanese President Emile Lahoud concerning "the latest
development in the region and result of Geneva summit" after his
arrival earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
On Lebanese Defense Minister Ghazi Zuetir's speech of inviting
Syrian troops into south Lebanon in the event of Israel's
unilateral pullout from south Lebanon, Shareh said this was
Zuetir's personal point of view, adding that the two countries
should speak in one voice or Israel will benefit from their
divergence. (Lebanon-Syria-Denial)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's proposals for
solving coalition crisis failed to convince his two irreconcilable
ruling partners, source in Barak's office said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Barak met with Education Minister Yossi Sarid, leader of left-
wing Meretz party, on Sunday afternoon in a latest effort to solve
the disputes between Meretz and the ultra-orthodox religious Shas
party, another pivotal party in Barak's ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
But Sarid turned down Barak's suggestions categorically, saying
that Barak's proposals were "unprecedented" and thus unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
During Barak's meeting with Labor and Social Affairs Minister
Eli Yishai last Thursday, Barak's bridging proposals were also
rejected.
</P>
<P>
(Israel-Coalition Crisis)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- Palestinian chief negotiator to the final-status talks
Yasser Abd-Rabbo said the talks held in Washington between March 21
and 28 failed to make substantial progress.
</P>
<P>
The talks focused on three main issues, namely the land, the
refugees and the future relations between Palestine and Israel, he
told reporters here on Sunday
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israelis discussed the last stage of the
redeployment of Israeli troops but failed to make headway due to
Israel's refusal to define the borders of Jewish settlements,
Jerusalem and the Israeli military bases which represent a
prerequisite of charting the maps of the last redeployment, Abd-
Rabbo said. (Palestinians-Israel-Talks) 
