<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Africa-Europe Summit Opportunity for New, Strategic Partnership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 2 (Xinhua) -- After over three years of
consultations and preparations, African and European leaders are
eventually to sit together to reshape bilateral relations with an
eye on strategic dialog and partnership, but the path is difficult.
</P>
<P>
Leaders from 53 African states and 15 European Union members
will gather in Cairo Monday for the first Africa-Europe summit,
proposed by Portugal in 1996 and finally endorsed by both the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) and the EU later 1999.
</P>
<P>
The leaders are expected at the two-day summit to discuss
economic, political and social development issues in Africa and
explore means of intensifying bilateral cooperation in these
fields.
</P>
<P>
The EU, with seven of its members former colonial powers in
Africa, gives about 15 billion U.S. dollars to Africa every five
years, more than any other single source.
</P>
<P>
Spurring the EU quest for a "new strategic partnership" with
Africa is the realization that the assistance it gives to the
region is failing to pull most countries out of underdevelopment.
</P>
<P>
Poverty, debts, wars and diseases are almost labels of Africa.
Half of its 700 million population are living in poverty and the
staggering 350 billion dollars external debts are choking African
economy.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest U.N. figures, African nations are
spending 23 billion dollars, or 30.9 percent of their exports, to
service the 350 billion dollars external debts every year.
</P>
<P>
As such, African local governments hardly have money for
education, infrastructure and technological upgrade. The poor
investment environment in turn scared away foreign investors,
hindering economic development and expansion.
</P>
<P>
In years, Africa has remained as a major raw material supplier,
relying heavily on exports of agricultural and mineral products for
hard currency. Simultaneously, they import industrial goods from
developed countries, which eats away most of their revenues.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of Africa's exports in the world's total amount
has been declining steadily in recent years, mainly due to the
countries' failure to open up industrial products markets, with raw
materials and semi-processed industrial products accounting for 80
percent of its total exports to the EU and North America.
</P>
<P>
Outcries for concrete EU help, such as the debt reduction or
forgiveness, more financial aid and investment, are strong among
the African states. They like the summit to concentrate on their
pressing concerns.
</P>
<P>
OAU Assistant Secretary-General for Eastern Africa Sigh Makhan
said Sunday that the African countries want the summit to discuss
issues "of primary concern to us" and "the partnership (with EU)
should be able to help us carry out economic reforms, including
structural adjustment, in the light of economic globalization."
</P>
<P>
Portugal's Foreign Minister Jaime Gama, whose country is holding
the EU Presidency, said on Sunday after the EU foreign ministers
meeting that "we have announced that, for the most poor countries,
we have a strategy of debt relief which is sound and will be
addressed in the appropriate framework of the international
financial institutions."
</P>
<P>
"Also, we have targets for alleviating Africa's poverty and
contributing to their efforts in close cooperation with the African
states. We are working seriously upon that," he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said tackling environment, AIDS, poverty and a number of
other social affairs "is a common responsibility, we must address
those issues in cooperation."
</P>
<P>
"And that is the reason why we are searching for a Euro-African
strategic partnership, which is being created in this (upcoming)
first Africa-Europe summit," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Europeans had seen the conference as a mainly political
event, seeking to put African conflict prevention, good governance,
democracy and human rights issues in the limelight.
</P>
<P>
Different as their hopes pinned on the conference, the sides
seemed to come to terms with each other at the eleventh hour on the
summit agenda, agreeing to address democracy, conflict prevention
and human rights alongside economic matters and development
concerns.
</P>
<P>
The wars and conflicts have left 3.5 million refugees on the
continent and further worsened the economic situation.
</P>
<P>
The summit is expected to issue a joint declaration, which will
stress the importance of carrying out cooperation between Africa
and the EU in various fields, and adopt a plan of action guiding
the concrete steps.
</P>
<P>
Observers believes, despite the unavoidable differences over
priority concerns between the two sides, the leaders from both
continents have seen the need for strategic partnership and
measures to solve the African problems because the problems like a
two-edge sword are detrimental not only to Africa, but also to
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the summit will duly provide an opportunity for the
Africans and Europeans to edge toward the achieving of their hoped-
for goals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000402.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak to Mediate between Syria, Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The chance to achieve peace
