<HEADLINE> African, EU FMs Meeting Ends With Agreement on Summit Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The foreign ministers of African and
the European Union (EU) states ended here on Sunday a one-day
meeting aimed at making final preparations for the first, two-day
Africa-Europe summit due Monday.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers reached agreement on the summit agenda
involving economic, political and social issues in Africa and ways
of enhancing cooperation over these issues between Africa and the
EU, Portuguese Foreign Minister Jaime Gama told reporters after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The ministers overcame the differences over the subjects to be
dealt with during the upcoming summit, said Gama, whose country is
holding EU's rotating presidency for the first half of 2000. But he
did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
While EU states mainly deem the summit as a political event to
take up democratization, human rights issues, conflict prevention
and good governance, the African countries are equally determined
to put emphasis on trade, investment, aid and debts.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers agreed to continue their countries'
efforts to seek intensive cooperation in resolving economic,
political and social problems in Africa, the Portuguese official
said.
</P>
<P>
A ministerial group, which is expected to be set up during the
summit, will meet soon after the summit to seek ways of carrying
out what will be decided by the leaders, Gama added.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also proposed that a second summit be held in 2003
to continue the efforts exerted by the EU and Africa to promote
cooperation in the development of the African continent, he said.
