<DOCNO> XIE20000402.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New IMF Chief Supports "State Barrier" for Capital Market:Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, April 2 (Xinhua)--Horst Koehler, the new German chief
of the International Monetary Fund (IMF), supported countries to
construct "national guard rails" for the capital market to prevent
possible financial crises, a news weekly reported.
</P>
<P>
At an interview with Germany's well-known "Der Spiegel"
magazine (this week issue), Koehler said he did not agree with the
"radical neo-liberal reform" of the United States.
</P>
<P>
A panel appointed by the U.S. parliament demanded developing
countries fully open their capital markets to western banks, a
policy that Koehler criticized as "of high risk."
</P>
<P>
"Every country must decide itself, how fast and with which
step it will open to the international financial market. I mean
the weaker should have fair chance," Koehler told Der Spiegel.
</P>
<P>
He called for "regulation framework of market economy for the
globalized world," and "guard rails for capital market."
</P>
<P>
"The experiences of economic transition in the east European
countries in recent ten years show that, the free market will have
its positive effect for everyone only after it has a functional
institutional basis," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore I take the 'open market or nothing' policy as
highly risky."
</P>
<P>
As an example, Koehler said the state should have the ability
to control inflow of short-term speculation investment with cash
depot.
</P>
<P>
Over his IMF reform plan, Koehler said: " the IMF should not
become a rescuer of private profits, although the private capital
market is the major initiative of stability and growth of world
economy. "
</P>
<P>
About the future roles of the world's two most important
financial institutions, namely the IMF and the World Bank, Kohler
said: "the World Bank's top duty will be fighting against poverty,
and the IMF should concentrate on crises preventing."
</P>
<P>
"But it is plausible that the two institutions achieve common
understandings," said Koehler.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Koehler told the "Welt am Sontag" newspaper that
he welcomed Asian countries' growing importance in the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The policy of the first German chief in a leading
international institution will "go on a conflict course against
the U.S." said Der Spiegel.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Koehler himself told the weekly that the U.S. had
tried to prevent his appointment until the last minute.
</P>
<P>
An official of the U.S. Financial Ministry had directly urged
him to quit the candidacy just before last month's IMF meeting
that picked him to lead the institution, Koehler told the magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
