<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Alliance Accepted for Using "Conservative" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Elections Canada, the federal
agency that registers party names, has accepted the use of the
word "Conservative" by the newly formed Canadian Reform
Conservative Alliance (CRCA) party.
</P>
<P>
The Calgary-based elections watchdog agency ruled Sunday that
the alliance of former Reformers and some provincial Conservatives
can use the name which, it said, "does not so resemble" other
party names in the country.
</P>
<P>
A local news release quoted Chief Electoral Officer Jean-Pierre
Kingsley as saying "I have accepted the application" by CRCA for
its official party name.
</P>
<P>
The ruling came after the federal Conservatives challenged the
new CRCA party for using the same word "Conservative", while
similar complaints were arising about possible name confusion from
the Canadian Action Party and the fledgling New Green Alliance.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian Action Party believes that the acronym CRCA plus
the word party (CRCAP) is too close to the short form of its own --
the CAP, while the New Green Alliance fears that people may get
confused about two Alliances.
</P>
<P>
The decision by Elections Canada was much to the relief of the
CRCA national council, which hailed the Sunday's ruling "a great
day for democracy."
</P>
<P>
"This party is an alliance between Reform and members of
Conservative parties across the country and we're glad to have
this fact recognized by Elections Canada," said Rod Love, a member
of the CRCA national council.
</P>
<P>
Reformers last month voted to replace the party with a unite-
the-right alliance under the banner of CRCA in a bid to unseat the
ruling Liberal in the next election.
</P>
<P>
Reformers, who enjoy the Official Opposition status in
Parliament with 60 seats, are optimistic about a victory with the
support from provincial Conservatives from Alberta and vote-rich
Ontario, which accounts for no less than 103 of the 301 seats in
the House of Commons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
