<HEADLINE> Volkswagen to Control Swedish Truck Maker Scania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, April 2 (Xinhua)-German automotive giant Volkswagen
Sunday stepped into the lucrative truck and bus market by
controlling Swedish Scania.
</P>
<P>
At a special meeting in Wolfsburg, the Volkswagen supervisory
board agreed to take over 34 percent of Scania voting right and
become its biggest owner.
</P>
<P>
The Volkswagen management called it a "bargain", since the
German group invested only 3 billion marks (1.5 billion dollars),
counting about 18.7 percent of Scania capital.
</P>
<P>
Scania, which sold 50,000 heavy trucks and buses last year, is
the third European truck maker behind Daimler-Chrysler and Volvo,
and its profit margin is among the world's highest.
</P>
<P>
The take-over directly attributed to an earlier EU veto
against Scania's planned merger with Volvo. The talks leading to
Volkswagen take-over began last Monday.
</P>
<P>
Volvo, also a Swedish automotive maker, owns 45.5 per cent of
Scania shares, but its voting right counts only 30.9 per cent.Thus
it become the second owner
</P>
<P>
Volkeswagen, annually producing only 9000 heavy trucks in
Latin America, has been interested in Scania since middle 1990s.
Their deal went to a deadlock two years ago after Scania demanded
a "high price." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
