<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Commando's Loss in Vedeno Ambush Adds Up to 43 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chechen rebels' ambush on a Russian OMON police convoy, and
their subsequent surprise attack against a second, federal relief
convoy, cost the federal units 43 men killed in all, said Russia's
deputy commandant of Vedeno district Colonel Ilya Lukin.
</P>
<P>
"The Russian police force lost 37 men, and the commandant's
company six men, with another 15 soldiers wounded. Out of all 49
federal servicemen of the ambushed troop, only five police
officers and one member of the commandant's company survived the
ambush uninjured," Lukin said.
</P>
<P>
The Russian military on Saturday said 32 bodies of Russian
servicemen had been found on the battlefield at the ambush site.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency quoted source from the Russian federal
forces in Chechnya as saying that the rebels had been tracking the
movement of the first and second convoys all along.
</P>
<P>
"They fired at the Russian armored vehicles with grenade
launchers and then at the OMON troops with silenced sniper rifles,
" said the source.
</P>
<P>
Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said Sunday that he
believes the federal elite OMON unit died in Chechnya due to
indiscipline by executive officials.
</P>
<P>
"The reasons for what took place lie above all in the field of
inadequately firm centralized management and lack of efficiency
among officials to cope with the duties allocated and endorsed by
Interior and Defense Ministers," he told journalists in Tajik
capital of Dushanbe, where he was inspecting a joint CIS military
exercise.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev said an investigation has already been conducted and
its
findings have been turned over to the Prosecutor's Office for "
determining who is to be blamed and to what extent." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
